  "y12g-ch1-1c-numerical-display": [
    { id: 1, question: "A histogram of test marks has a long tail extending to LOW values. The distribution is:", options: ["Positively skewed", "Negatively skewed", "Symmetric", "Bimodal"], correctAnswer: 1, explanation: "✓ Tail to the left = negatively skewed. ✗ Positive skew = tail right. ✗ Symmetric has equal tails. Concept: shape descriptors. Common mistake: naming skew by where the peak is (it's the tail that determines skew)." },
    { id: 2, question: "When choosing a class width for a histogram, the BEST guideline is:", options: ["Use exactly 10 classes always", "Use 5–15 classes that reveal the shape without losing detail", "Use as many classes as data points", "Use class width equal to the mean"], correctAnswer: 1, explanation: "✓ 5–15 classes typically balances detail and clarity. ✗ Always 10 is rigid. ✗ Too many classes = noisy. Concept: histogram construction. Common mistake: using too few classes, hiding skew or modality." },
    { id: 3, question: "A histogram shows a clear single peak with roughly equal tails. Best description:", options: ["Skewed left", "Skewed right", "Approximately symmetric and unimodal", "Bimodal"], correctAnswer: 2, explanation: "✓ Single peak + balanced = symmetric unimodal. Concept: shape vocabulary. Common mistake: mistaking small irregularities for bimodality." },
    { id: 4, question: "On a histogram, the modal class is the one with:", options: ["The widest bar", "The tallest bar (highest frequency)", "The middle position", "The smallest frequency"], correctAnswer: 1, explanation: "✓ Mode = tallest bar. ✗ Width is fixed if classes are equal. Concept: locating mode from a histogram. Common mistake: reading frequency from horizontal axis." },
    { id: 5, question: "If a histogram is positively skewed, then typically:", options: ["mean < median", "mean ≈ median", "mean > median", "mode > mean > median"], correctAnswer: 2, explanation: "✓ Positive skew pulls the mean toward the long right tail. ✗ Symmetric ⇒ mean ≈ median. Concept: relationship between shape and centre. Common mistake: confusing direction of inequality." },
    { id: 6, question: "A histogram with two distinct peaks is described as:", options: ["Skewed", "Symmetric", "Bimodal", "Uniform"], correctAnswer: 2, explanation: "✓ Two peaks = bimodal — often a sign of two subgroups. Concept: modality. Common mistake: missing bimodality by using too few classes." },
    { id: 7, question: "A test-score histogram (n = 200) is roughly symmetric with no outliers. The most appropriate measures are:", options: ["Median and IQR", "Mean and standard deviation", "Mode and range", "Geometric mean"], correctAnswer: 1, explanation: "✓ Symmetric, no outliers ⇒ mean and SD. ✗ Median/IQR preferred for skewed/outlier data. Concept: matching summary statistics to shape. Common mistake: defaulting to median/IQR regardless of shape." },
    { id: 8, question: "Reading from a histogram with class boundaries 30–<40 (frequency 8) and 40–<50 (frequency 12), the percentage of values in [30, 50) when n = 50 is:", options: ["20%", "24%", "32%", "40%"], correctAnswer: 3, explanation: "✓ (8+12)/50 × 100 = 40%. ✗ 32% miscounts. Concept: cumulative frequency from histogram. Common mistake: failing to add adjacent bars." },
    { id: 9, question: "Which statement about a histogram with an obvious right outlier is MOST accurate?", options: ["The mean is unaffected", "The median is heavily affected", "The mean increases more than the median", "Both are pulled equally"], correctAnswer: 2, explanation: "✓ Mean is sensitive to extreme values; median is resistant. Concept: robustness of median. Common mistake: assuming the median moves with extreme values." },
    { id: 10, question: "When describing a numerical distribution from a histogram, you should comment on (in order):", options: ["Spread, then shape, then any outliers", "Shape, centre, spread, and outliers", "Outliers only", "The mode only"], correctAnswer: 1, explanation: "✓ Standard VCAA description: shape, centre, spread, outliers. Concept: report structure. Common mistake: omitting one of the four required elements — costly in Exam 2." },
  ],

